This is Filament Runout Sensor with extruder for Sigma3d Printer. You need a microswitch with bearing... The switch should be connected as NC to X max on ramps board.
In Marlin pin.h definition of your board change the line
define FIL_RUNOUT_PIN 2
2 for Xmax pin
15 For Ymax pin
19 for Z Max Pin
In Configuration.h enable the filament_runout_sensor, uncomment the first line,

title: Proxxon to Dremel mini saw adapter

description.text:
Behold, my 1st creation for 3D printing: an adapter to allow Proxxon rotary tools to use the Dremel mini saw attachment (670). I switched to Proxxon after learning it uses a brushless motor (yes, I'm a spec. whore) and because my 7 year old Dremel 300 was losing torque. I could use every Dremel accessory except the mini saw until now thanks to 3D printing.

Unlike some of the other Dremel mini saw tables on this site, using the angled saw attachment lets the blade be perpendicular to the surface anywhere without the body of the tool getting in the way. I've used it to cut large sheets of acrylic.

STL file is ready for printing. Also included is the original Blender file that has some extra shapes (e.g. the 2D profile that's rotated around the Y axis to generate the cylinder). I had to file / sand the inside by ~0.5mm before the tool would fit. Also, there seems to be some printing imperfections near the bottom due to the large overhang. Printing it upright will eliminate it, but then it will lose strength along the Z-axis.

description.text:
Pretty much the same box design I uploaded before, except this one has rounded corners.  This makes the box feel better in your hand and you don't get gouged if you need to carry it around in your pocket. You can vary the radius of the corner from about 0.1 mm up to around 10mm.  
Enjoy!  
Update: 12/2/13 - Version 1.1  
I noticed that the boxes were ending up a little under dimension and tracked the problem back to too few facets on the rounded corners.  I reworked the roundedRect module to use cylinders with facet count control ($fa and $fs). I cranked up the number of facets and the corners are smoother and overall dimensions are closer to the mark now.  This increased the compile time on OpenSCAD, but you can tinker with $fa and $fas in the roundedRect module if you want to tune compile time vs. smoothness.  I also left the original version if you prefer to use it.  
Enjoy!

description.text:
The Acetone Smoothie spins ABS-printed objects inside an Acetone-vapor vessel, resulting in a uniformly glossy surface without base scars. Acetone Smoothie can be made as simple or as sophisticated as you like. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qZ2M2RDUTAQ

The Smoothie is designed avoid pressure buildup by providing a vent in the 1st flange. Make sure you leave enough clearance between the spinning rod and the lid of your vessel. This means, that Acetone vapour will escape, which may be a hazard with DC BRUSHED MOTORS which produce sparks. STEPPER MOTORS do NOT produce sparks. USE IN WELL VENTILATED AREA

The simple version

If you want the simplest implementation and still get 90% of the benefit, this is for you.

  • A $4 geared DC motor (http://bit.ly/2gGYym8) - READ NOTE ABOUT SPARKS ABOVE
  • No bearings. You can modify the Smoothie_Flange1 and Smoothie_Flange2 STLs so that the axis hole is 5mm or print plastic bushings to fit in the flanges.

The advanced version

If you want to precisely control the rotation speed, pausing, changing of direction, timing etc., then this is for you. You could control the heating if you wanted to - not covered here - with a silicone heating pad, if you wanted to!

  • $3 stepper motor such as 28YBJ-48 (http://bit.ly/2gY0zbK)
  • $3 Arduino Nano (http://bit.ly/2g2g54g)
  • $5 Ball Bearings (http://bit.ly/2h5SFMu) or Brass Bearings $4 (http://bit.ly/2gYxSxH)

You will also need

  • 2x 15mm M3 Hex bolts and matching nuts
  • A glass jar (size depends on your projects)
  • A 5mm rod or tube (length depends on your projects)

Notes

I use hot glue to attach the Smoothie to jar's lid.

As heat source I use the printer's heated bed.

I found out that attaching the part to the rod with Hot Glue works the best. To make life easier, I sometimes incorporate tabs with a 5mm hole inside the object. Then just insert the rod inside the object and secure it with hot glue on the exposed end.

The Moai used in the rendering is from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:149271

description.text:
Mount for inductive Probe (12mm / 18mm) for Anycubic Prusa I3 metal X carriage.

The mount consists of two parts, the probe holder and the carriage mount. The carriage mount part is available in a straight version that enables easier assembly but is quite on the edge with the X end stop switch. The angled version keeps the probe clear from end stop but there hardly is a way to detach it with mounted carriage.

There are some instructables like this one, explaining how to connect the probe using a voltage divider. I use a tiny reed relais to run the probe parallel to the mechanical Z endstop that I wanted to keep as fallback.

The parts are designed a little tight, printed with PLA screw holes and fittings will need a bit of sanding before they connect properly. 1 additional M3x10 Phillips screw is supposed to hold things in place.

The main task in mounting an inductive probe is to get it as orthogonal as possible to the bed. If it is only a little out of angle the detection range will be reduced and become unreliable. If using Marlin, I'd suggest to update to 1.1.0 RC8 or later.

title: Single WS2812 LED Holder for GepRC ZX4, ZX5, ZX6
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A simple holder for a single addressable LED (e.g. https://www.aliexpress.com/item/100pcs-ws2812-individually-addressable-rgb-full-color-ws2812b-led-emitter-chip-with-white-black-heatsink-dc/32619250295.html) to mount on the existing two vertical spacers.

I build the ZX5 in plus configuration so there is a gap at the bottom to get over the hardware - this is useful for running your battery cable through if you build an X.

Flip STL 180 degrees to print, then try and get some support in around where the LED will sit just to keep it round.

Hopefully self explanatory from the STL file, but basically solder 3 wires on the rear pads of the LED, then run the wires through the hole, place the LED with a drop of superglue on the rear where it touches the mount. Press together and hold until glue has set, then after you are installed and getting frisky with the hot glue, gunge up your solder joints on the LED and a bit extra for good measure and you should be problem free.

description.text:
Fully 3D printed RC snowmobile. Fully functional with working suspension. Works surprisingly well in snow. The only issues I had, is the front control arms that snaps if you jump to high.

This is not a easy build and you need some CAD skills to make motor mounts and
if necessary some other parts. You also need some RC skills to get the best motor setup and calculate the gearing.

What you need besides plastic:
RC stuff like transmitter and so on
Motor, speed controller, and transmission between motor and drive shaft.
5x150mm steel rods for steering axles (cut to fit)
4x400m steel rods for the rest of the axles. Like the shock absorber, suspension and drive shaft (cut to fit)
4pc Springs for shock absorbers inner diameter 7mm and ~17mm long depending on how hard suspension you want.
6pc Ball bearings 8x4x3mm for drive shaft, upper wheels and big lower wheels.
Some stiff 2mm wire to use as wear rods under the skis.
some M3 screws with nuts
*4 and 5mm set screw shaft collars or equivalent

The chassis is glued together with hot glue. The bearing bracket is bolted to the chassis with M3 screws and so is the front suspension. All the steel rods is fitted with set screw shaft collars. The seat is held to the chassis by magnets at the rear and is easy to remove to change battery.

The power plant and gearing is a little tricky. I used a hobbyking 36mm 550w inrunner and toothed pulleys with a gearing of 9 to 42. I chose this setup because I thought needed the power but its to overpowered and a little heavy. I recommend to use a smaller high torque engine.

Please send me your questions and I will update with more information.

RepRap

Printer:

Mendel

Doesn't Matter

0,3

Notes:

I used resolution 0,3 because I'm lacy but 0,1 is recommended for better finish. Support is needed at the front half of the chassis and the rear suspension runner. If you print in ABS you gonna have some problems with warping. I used Kapton tape and glue to prevent warping. I think PET is the ideal plastic for this build.

The track is printed in Ninjaflex Shore 85A. But other flexible brands works as well. No support for the track.

description.text: Scale model of Saturn and its complex ring system, with the Cassini Spacecraft's 2017 trajectory illustrated. Southern hemisphere is cut off so the planet and rings sit on a flat surface. The planet is an accurately oblate hemi-spheroid, surrounded by main rings A, B, and C, plus illustrations of the inner D Ring and the outer F Ring at their scale radial distance (of course all the rings are way thicker than scale). The Cassini Division, and the finer Enke and Maxwell gaps are all represented. Extent of the "planet shadow" is accurate for September 2017. Edge of the accurately inclined "sail" illustrates the Cassini Spacecraft's 2017 proximal-orbit trajectory. No support material is generated. If you are one of the people whom I've given a print of this to, note that I printed it at home; no tax dollars were harmed! Please note there's a "like" button up there! Technical poster: http://people.artcenter.edu/doody/3dposter.pdf Additional variations of this object: http://spacecraftkits.com/3d I have a .gcode file that will print a refined version of this scale model onto its own square black background. Looks great. The .gcode file runs on a Bukobot Duo using black and white 3.00 mm diameter PLA filament; this .gcode was kindly edited by Rich Cameron. Contact me if you'd like a copy. (See "Contact" at spacecraftkits.com) Back story: Cassini is planning to jump (via a seemingly magical Titan gravity assist) into a series of twenty-two orbits that are in very close proximity to the planet in April 2017, which will take the spacecraft in between the atmosphere and inner rings (like the model shows!). It's risky, so it's being done very near the end of the mission. Then Cassini will end its 20-year mission by plunging into Saturn in September 2017. More at: http://saturn.jpl.nasa.gov

Made by specifying the planet, rings, shadow shape and spacecraft trajectory for May 2017, in OpenSCAD. Output as .stl file. Developed and tested using Repetier, Slic3r and a RepRap FDM 8-inch machine (http://bukobot.com). When slicing, set for concentric fill so the rings appear "ringy." I also added a simple "2017" character block (TinkerCAD) as .stl file just before printing; it conveniently unites the outer parts of the ring system with the planet-shadow to help in removing the delicate ring system from printer bed and displaying. The rings' thickness is enormously exaggerated in order to be visible at all in a scale model. In addition, the densest ring, the B Ring, is very thick in the model just to lend some mechanical stability to the thing. If you can print in two colors, look for SaturnBaseplate.stl to print in a contrasting color beneath this model. More discussion and details on how to print this object may be found on http://SpacecraftKits.com.

description.text:
I am inspired by the art of Kumiko Shoji and I created a lamp with simple geometric patterns.

In traditional Japanese architecture, a shōji (障子?) is a door, window or room divider consisting of translucent paper over a frame of wood which holds together a lattice of wood or bamboo.

In modern Japan, shoji means wooden sliding doors with translucent paper on. These doors slide on wood tracks very smoothly and quietly, work as a room divider or window coverings.

Craftsmanship - “Kumiko” woodwork technique
“Kumiko”, in short, is a delicate technique of assembling wooden pieces without nails.
Thinly slit wooden pieces are grooved, punched and mortised, and then are assembled and joined one by one with plane, saw, chisel and other tools while fine adjustments are made. The “Kumiko” woodwork technique was developed in Japan in the Asuka Era (600-700 AD) and has since been refined and passed down through generations of craftsmen.

I printed the lamp wood filament. Instead of rice paper was used baking paper. All parts are glued.
You can create your own model using simple patterns and combining them. You can change the size of the model and color of the filament.
You can make original gifts to your friends using Kumiko Shoji style.

This lamp is designed for candles with a diameter of 40 mm.
